\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 3.       Ottelia}       Pers.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By J.E. Dandy. 
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Stems short. Leaves basal, petiolate. Flowers usually hermaphrodite, insect-pollinated above the water-surface. Spathes tubular, pedunculate, usually 1-flowered. Petals much longer and wider than the sepals. Stamens 6-20. Ovary sessile within the spathe; styles 3-15, 2-fid, free.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. O. alismoides} (L.) Pers., {\i Syn. Pl.}{\b  1}: 400 (1805). Leaves varying greatly in size, up to 20 cm wide, submerged or partly emersed, broadly ovate to lanceolate, subcordate to cuneate at the base, 7- to 11-veined. Spathes with 5-10 longitudinal wings. Petals 20-30 mm, obovate, white, with a yellow spot at the base. Stamens 6-9. Styles 6-9. 2n = 22.{\i  Naturalized in rice-fields in N. Italy.} [It.] ({\i S.E. Asia, N.E. Africa, Australasia.})
\par

